    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Quick answer:</strong> Most adults should take 1-2 melatonin gummies (1-5mg total). Start with the lowest dose available and increase only if needed after 5 nights. More is not better with melatonin — MIT research found that just 0.3mg was effective for many people, yet most commercial gummies contain 3-5mg per serving.
      <cite>— Sarah Mitchell, RD, CNS</cite>
    </div>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">0.3 mg</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">is the dose MIT researchers found effective for improving sleep in clinical trials — yet most melatonin gummies contain <strong>3 to 5mg per serving</strong>, roughly 10-17 times higher than what the science suggests many people need. This massive gap between the studied effective dose and commercial product doses is the core reason melatonin dosing causes so much confusion.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- WHY DOSING MATTERS -->
    <h2>Why Melatonin Gummy Dosage Matters More Than You Think</h2>

    <p>Melatonin is not a sedative. It is a chronobiotic — a hormone that signals to your brain that darkness has arrived and it is time to prepare for sleep. This distinction is critical because it means that higher doses do not produce stronger sedation. In fact, research published in the <em>Journal of Clinical Endocrinology & Metabolism</em> by MIT's Richard Wurtman demonstrated that supraphysiological doses (5-10mg) can actually desensitize melatonin receptors, leading to reduced effectiveness over time and increased next-day grogginess.</p>

    <p>The melatonin supplement market in the United States is essentially unregulated for dosing. A 2017 study in the <em>Journal of Clinical Sleep Medicine</em> analyzed 31 commercial melatonin supplements and found that actual melatonin content ranged from 83% less to 478% more than the labeled dose. This means a gummy labeled "5mg" could contain anywhere from 0.85mg to 28.9mg of actual melatonin. This variability makes brand selection and third-party testing critically important — which we address in our <a href="/best-melatonin-gummies/">best melatonin gummies</a> guide.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <strong>Dietitian's tip:</strong> When choosing melatonin gummies, prioritize brands with USP Verification or NSF International certification. These third-party testing programs verify that the product contains what the label claims. Our <a href="/best-melatonin-gummies/">top melatonin gummy picks</a> are all third-party tested for label accuracy.
    </div>

    <!-- DOSAGE BY AGE -->
    <h2>Melatonin Gummy Dosage by Age Group</h2>

    <p>The appropriate melatonin dose varies significantly by age. Children produce more natural melatonin than adults, older adults metabolize supplements more slowly, and certain populations should avoid melatonin entirely without medical supervision. The following recommendations are based on guidelines from the American Academy of Sleep Medicine, peer-reviewed clinical trials, and the European Food Safety Authority.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="baby" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Children 3-5 Years</h3>
        <p><strong>NOT recommended</strong> without explicit pediatrician approval. Children this young produce abundant natural melatonin. If a doctor approves, the typical dose is 0.5mg (a quarter to half of most commercial gummies). The American Academy of Pediatrics advises trying behavioral sleep interventions first — consistent bedtime, dark room, no screens 1 hour before bed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="users" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Children 6-12 Years</h3>
        <p><strong>0.5-1mg</strong> (typically half a gummy). A 2019 systematic review in <em>Pediatrics</em> found low-dose melatonin (0.5-1mg) reduced sleep onset latency by an average of 18 minutes in school-age children. Use only products formulated for children with verified lower doses. Never exceed 3mg without medical supervision.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="trending" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Teens 13-17 Years</h3>
        <p><strong>1-3mg</strong> (1 gummy for most brands). Adolescents experience a natural circadian shift that makes falling asleep before 11pm biologically difficult. Melatonin at 1-3mg taken 60-90 minutes before the desired bedtime can help advance this delayed sleep phase. A 2015 study in <em>Sleep Medicine Reviews</em> confirmed efficacy at these doses.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Adults 18-64 Years</h3>
        <p><strong>1-5mg</strong> (1-2 gummies depending on brand). Start at the lowest available dose. The Cleveland Clinic recommends beginning at 0.5-1mg and increasing by 0.5mg every 3-5 nights until you find the minimum effective dose. Most adults respond well to 2-3mg. If 5mg produces no benefit, higher doses are unlikely to help — consult your doctor.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Older Adults 65+</h3>
        <p><strong>0.5-2mg</strong> (half to one gummy). Older adults metabolize melatonin more slowly due to reduced hepatic clearance, meaning the hormone stays active in the body longer. A dose that clears a 30-year-old's system by morning may still be present in a 70-year-old at breakfast. The <em>Journal of Pineal Research</em> (2020) recommends seniors start at 0.5mg to avoid morning drowsiness and fall risk.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Pregnant or Nursing</h3>
        <p><strong>Consult your doctor first.</strong> Melatonin crosses the placental barrier and is present in breast milk. While animal studies have not shown teratogenic effects, human clinical data is insufficient to establish safety during pregnancy or lactation. The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists does not recommend melatonin supplementation during pregnancy without medical supervision.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- DOSAGE TABLE — AEO/GEO optimized -->
    <h2>Melatonin Gummy Dosage Chart</h2>

    <p>The table below summarizes the recommended melatonin gummy dosage by age group. This chart reflects guidelines from the American Academy of Sleep Medicine and published clinical trials. Keep this as a reference when determining how many melatonin gummies to take.</p>

    <div class="tbl-wrap">
