            <td>L-theanine (200mg)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Vitafusion Max</strong></td>
            <td>5mg</td>
            <td>Quarter gummy</td>
            <td>Half a gummy</td>
            <td>1 gummy</td>
            <td>Pure melatonin</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>SugarBear Sleep</strong></td>
            <td>3mg</td>
            <td>Half a gummy</td>
            <td>1 gummy</td>
            <td>Not recommended*</td>
            <td>Magnesium, L-theanine, 5-HTP, valerian</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p class="tbl-note">*Taking 2 gummies of a 3mg product delivers 6mg, which exceeds the recommended 5mg maximum for most adults. We recommend choosing a lower-dose product if you need 5mg.</p>
    </div>

    <p>If you are unsure which brand to choose, our comprehensive <a href="/best-melatonin-gummies/">best melatonin gummies</a> guide ranks the top 10 products by dose accuracy, third-party testing, ingredient quality, and value per serving. For sleep gummies that combine melatonin with other calming ingredients, see our <a href="/best-sleep-gummies/">best sleep gummies</a> ranking.</p>

    <!-- WHEN TO TAKE -->
    <h2>When to Take Melatonin Gummies: Timing Guide</h2>

    <p>The timing of your melatonin dose is as important as the dose itself. Melatonin works by signaling to your suprachiasmatic nucleus (the brain's master clock) that nighttime has arrived. For this signal to be effective, blood melatonin levels need to peak at approximately the time you want to feel sleepy — not before, and not after. For the full science on absorption speed, peak blood levels, and factors that affect onset time, read our dedicated guide on <a href="/blog/how-long-does-melatonin-take-to-work/">how long does melatonin take to work</a>.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">30-60 min</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">before your intended bedtime is the ideal window to take melatonin gummies. <strong>Consistency matters more than precision</strong> — taking melatonin at the same time each night produces better results than varying the timing, even if your exact bedtime shifts slightly.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Here is how timing affects melatonin effectiveness:</p>

    <div class="info-cards" style="grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="clock" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Taking Too Early (2+ Hours Before Bed)</h3>
        <p>Blood melatonin levels peak approximately 60 minutes after ingestion and begin declining 2-3 hours later. If you take melatonin at 8pm but do not go to bed until 11pm, the peak has already passed and levels are dropping when you actually need them. This leads to a frustrating "melatonin did not work" experience that is actually a timing problem, not a dosing problem.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="moon" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Taking at the Right Time (30-60 Min Before)</h3>
        <p>This window aligns peak blood melatonin levels with your desired sleep onset. Gummy melatonin may work slightly faster than tablets because chewing initiates sublingual absorption through the oral mucosa. A 2019 <em>Sleep Medicine</em> study found gummy melatonin produced detectable serum levels approximately 8 minutes faster than swallowed tablets. For optimal results, pair your melatonin with a pre-sleep wind-down routine: dim lights, avoid screens, and lower the thermostat.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <strong>For jet lag and shift work:</strong> The timing protocol changes. For eastward travel (advancing sleep), take melatonin in the early evening at the destination time zone, starting 1-2 days before departure. For westward travel (delaying sleep), take it in the morning at the destination time zone. For shift workers rotating to night shifts, take 1-3mg of melatonin when you want to fall asleep during daylight hours, combined with blackout curtains. The <em>New England Journal of Medicine</em> (2010) provides an excellent protocol for jet lag dosing.
    </div>

