      <h2>Melatonin Gummy Dosage — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take 2 melatonin gummies at once?</summary><p>It depends on the dose per gummy. If each gummy contains 1-2.5mg, taking two (2-5mg total) is within the standard adult range. If each gummy is 5mg, taking two delivers 10mg — a supraphysiological dose likely to cause grogginess and headaches. Always check the milligrams per gummy on the label before doubling up.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What should I do if one melatonin gummy doesn't work?</summary><p>Before increasing your dose, verify timing (30-60 minutes before bed), environment (dark, cool room, no screens), and consistency (try for at least 5 consecutive nights). If one gummy at optimal timing still has no effect after a week, increase by half or one additional gummy. If 5mg total has no effect, consult your healthcare provider.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take melatonin gummies every night?</summary><p>Short-term nightly use (up to 3 months) is considered safe for healthy adults. Melatonin does not cause physical dependency. Many sleep specialists recommend cycling — 3 weeks on, 1 week off — to prevent psychological reliance. For nightly use beyond 3 months, consult your doctor.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are melatonin gummies safe for kids?</summary><p>With pediatrician approval, children 6-12 can use 0.5-1mg melatonin. Children under 3 should not use melatonin without explicit medical guidance. Always try behavioral sleep strategies first — consistent bedtime, limited screens, dark room. Use children's formulations with third-party testing.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What happens if I take too many melatonin gummies?</summary><p>Common symptoms of excessive melatonin include severe morning grogginess, headaches, nausea, dizziness, vivid nightmares, and paradoxical insomnia. Symptoms typically resolve within 12-24 hours. If a child consumes multiple melatonin gummies, contact Poison Control at 1-800-222-1222.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take melatonin with other sleep supplements?</summary><p>Many melatonin gummies already include L-theanine, magnesium, chamomile, or valerian. Do not stack separate melatonin with a multi-ingredient sleep supplement that also contains melatonin. Never combine melatonin with prescription sleep medications or alcohol without consulting your doctor.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Does melatonin dosage depend on body weight?</summary><p>For adults, no — melatonin dosing is not strictly weight-based because it functions as a circadian signal, not a sedative drug. Individual sensitivity matters more than body size. For children, pediatricians may use approximately 0.05mg per kilogram of body weight as a starting guideline.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are melatonin gummies stronger than melatonin pills?</summary><p>At the same milligram dose, gummies and pills deliver equivalent total melatonin. However, gummies may produce slightly faster onset because chewing allows some sublingual absorption. A 2019 study found gummy melatonin reached detectable blood levels about 8 minutes sooner than tablets. Total absorption and efficacy are equivalent.</p></details>
